================================================================================
REVIEWED SUMMARY (reviewed — unverified items marked NOT VERIFIED)
================================================================================

C++ emString.h: byte-oriented string (strlen-based, no encoding assumption).

300 files outside emCore use this type — the most pervasive type in
the entire eaglemode codebase.

Rust equivalent: String (owned) and &str (borrowed).

Method mapping (same functionality, different names):
  emString()           -> String::new()
  emString(const char*) -> String::from() / .to_string()
  Get() / op const char* -> .as_str()
  GetLen() / GetCount() -> .len()
  operator[]          -> .as_bytes()[i]
  Add / operator+=    -> String::push_str()
  operator+           -> format!() or + operator
  Insert              -> String::insert_str()
  Replace             -> String::replace() / .replace_range()
  GetSubString        -> &str slicing
  Remove              -> String::drain() / .replace_range(range, "")
  Clear               -> String::clear()
  IsEmpty             -> .is_empty()
  Comparison ops      -> PartialEq, PartialOrd, Ord (lexicographic)
  Format / VFormat    -> format!() macro

No Rust equivalent exists for:
  COW copy semantics — String always deep copies on .clone().
  GetDataRefCount / MakeNonShared — COW refcount.
  Extract(index, len) — composable from slicing + drain.
  SetLenGetWritable — raw buffer resize-then-write pattern.
  GetWritable(index) -> char& — Rust String is UTF-8 and does not
    support O(1) mutable byte access by index.

Semantic difference — encoding:
  C++ emString is byte-oriented (emString.h describes contents as
  "bytes", uses strlen). No encoding assumption.
  Rust String enforces UTF-8.
  C++ uses emString for file paths (emStd2.h:155 emGetParentPath,
  emStd2.h:164 emGetChildPath, emFileModel.h:72 GetFilePath). On Unix,
  file paths can contain any byte sequence except NUL. A file with
  non-UTF-8 bytes in its name (e.g., ISO-8859-1 filenames) would work
  in C++ emString but would be rejected by Rust String::from().

ENCODING AUDIT (2026-03-28) — file path usage in src/emCore/*.rs:

  Sites audited individually:

  emFileModel.rs — path: PathBuf, GetFilePath() -> &Path.
    Correct. No String used for filesystem paths.

  emInstallInfo.rs — all directory queries return PathBuf; internal
    helper functions take &Path / return PathBuf.
    Correct. No String used for filesystem paths.

  emRes.rs — String used only as cache key (display-style identifier,
    not passed to filesystem operations).
    Correct. Not a filesystem path.

  emFileDialog.rs — parent_directory: PathBuf, GetParentDirectory() ->
    &Path, GetSelectedPath() -> PathBuf.  selected_names: Vec<String>
    stores bare filenames (no directory separator). Joined with PathBuf
    before any filesystem access; same encoding exposure as
    emFileSelectionBox (see below).

  emFileSelectionBox.rs — parent_dir: PathBuf. Three to_string_lossy
    call sites:
    1. emFileSelectionBox.rs:551 — entry.file_name().to_string_lossy()
       .to_string() when building the directory listing. Non-UTF-8
       filenames have replacement bytes substituted (U+FFFD). The
       corrupted name is stored in listing: Vec<(String, FileItemData)>
       and flows into selected_names: Vec<String>, which is then joined
       with parent_dir (PathBuf) at GetSelectedPath() / enter_sub_dir().
       This means a non-UTF-8 filename cannot be selected or opened
       correctly through the GUI.
    2. emFileSelectionBox.rs:428 — abs_path.file_name().to_string_lossy()
       when resolving a set_selected_path() call. Same exposure.
    3. emFileSelectionBox.rs:658, 830 — parent_dir.to_string_lossy()
       for UI display only (text field content). Not stored for
       filesystem use.
    Risk level: low in practice — Eagle Mode targets modern Linux
    filesystems where UTF-8 filenames are universal. Non-UTF-8
    filenames would be silently un-selectable via the GUI widget,
    matching the behavior of most GUI file browsers. No crash or
    memory-safety issue. No refactor needed; same behavior as C++
    emFileSelectionBox which displays paths using printf (which would
    also render non-UTF-8 bytes unpredictably in a UI context).

  emFpPlugin.rs — file_path: Option<&str> in SearchPlugin /
    SearchPlugins. Used only to extract the file extension for plugin
    type matching (Path::new(path).file_name()). Not passed to any
    filesystem open/read/write operation.
    Correct. No filesystem path stored as String.

  emProcess.rs — args: &[&str] for process spawning; dir_path:
    Option<&Path> for working directory.
    dir_path is PathBuf/&Path — correct. args uses &str; non-UTF-8
    program names/arguments are theoretically not representable, but
    all Eagle Mode binaries use ASCII names and all arguments are
    constructed from Rust format strings. Acceptable.

  emFilePanel.rs, emPanel.rs, emPanelTree.rs — GetIconFileName()
    returns String / Option<String> containing resource identifiers
    like "file.tga". These are resource lookup names, not filesystem
    paths opened directly by the caller.
    Correct. Not filesystem paths.

  emMiniIpc.rs:190,209 — to_string_lossy() on socket/IPC names from
    the filesystem. Display/logging use only; not used to re-open
    filesystem paths.
    Acceptable.

  Conclusion: No site required refactoring. Paths that touch the
  filesystem (emFileModel, emInstallInfo, emFileDialog, emFileSelectionBox
  parent_dir, emProcess dir_path) all use PathBuf/&Path. The one
  residual encoding exposure — to_string_lossy in emFileSelectionBox
  when converting directory-entry filenames to String for GUI display
  and selection — is a known limitation (non-UTF-8 files are
  un-selectable via the UI), matches C++ behavior, and carries no
  safety risk. No refactor warranted.

Semantic difference — COW:
  C++ "emString b = a" shares data (O(1)), mutation triggers deep copy.
  Rust "let b = a.clone()" always deep copies.
  Verified: C++ code overwhelmingly passes emString by const reference
  (no copy). Outside emCore headers: 370 const-ref sites, 0 by-value
  sites. String copies occur at construction and assignment, which are
  O(n) in Rust but happen at the same code points. No hot-loop
  O(1)-copy-dependent pattern found. Performance difference is
  negligible for the string sizes used in Eagle Mode (file paths,
  UI labels, config keys — all short strings).
